48:05.850 --> 48:12.523 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight,
we pause for
a "PBS NewsHour" essay.

48:12.623 --> 48:17.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeff Greenfield is a seasoned
political journalist
and author, and he shares his
belief about

48:17.962 --> 48:21.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the end of trust by Americans in
this country's
institutions.

48:22.066 --> 48:25.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Greenfield has titled his essay
"In Nothing
We Trust."

48:25.703 --> 48:29.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFF GREENFIELD, Journalist:
It's not exactly
breaking news that we're
entering this political

48:29.573 --> 48:32.409 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
high season in the winter of our
discontent.

48:32.510 --> 48:37.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The polls and the political
rhetoric speak
to a mood of anger, distrust,
even outright

48:37.782 --> 48:43.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
betrayal. But take a look beyond
the political
realm, and you will find
something that runs

48:43.320 --> 48:47.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
longer than the current
campaign, and deeper
than politics.

48:47.491 --> 48:52.863 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The unhappy fact is that
Americans' trust
in just about all our
institutions has been

48:52.963 --> 48:59.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in a long, almost unbroken
decline. Our trust
in government? A Pew Research
poll last November

48:59.804 --> 49:05.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
found that only 19 percent of us
trusted the
government to do what was right
all or most

49:05.442 --> 49:09.146 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the time. That's close to an
historic low.

49:09.246 --> 49:17.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the real story here is how
long that distrust
has been festering. Go back to
1964, when

49:17.855 --> 49:23.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the U.S. was in the midst of a
long period
of economic growth, when the
Cold War was

49:23.394 --> 49:27.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
easing, when a major civil
rights bill had
just been passed.

49:27.665 --> 49:33.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Back then, 77 percent trusted
the government
to do the right thing all or
most of the time.

49:33.604 --> 49:40.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A decade later, after a divisive
war, racial
and generational unrest, a
president driven

49:40.511 --> 49:46.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from office in scandal, the
number had dropped
to 36 percent. And in the four
decades since,

49:46.617 --> 49:52.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it has never hit 50 percent, not
even in the
surge of patriotism after 9/11.

49:52.423 --> 49:58.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's about 40 years' worth of
alienation
from the government of, by and
for people.

49:58.562 --> 50:03.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Well, OK, but that's the
government. We are
a nation born in revolt, with a
permanent

50:03.801 --> 50:10.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
skepticism about our leaders.
But now look
at our feelings about other
major institutions,

50:10.207 --> 50:15.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the picture, painted by a
series of Gallup
surveys going back decades,
finds a disturbingly

50:15.613 --> 50:17.381 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
similar pattern.

50:17.481 --> 50:22.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our churches? Two-thirds of us
had a lot of
trust in our religious
institutions back in

50:22.152 --> 50:32.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
1973. Now barely 42 percent do.
Banks? Trust
has gone from 60 percent back in
1979 to 28

50:32.129 --> 50:37.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
percent now. Our public schools?
More than
half were trusting at the end of
the '70s.

50:38.035 --> 50:40.237 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Barely three in 10 are today.

50:40.337 --> 50:46.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Organized labor? Big business?
The medical
system? The presidency? All get
low grades.

50:46.277 --> 50:51.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And before you ask, 21 percent
profess a lot
of faith in television news,
less than half

50:52.049 --> 50:55.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the percentage that did so
little more than
20 years ago.

50:55.152 --> 51:00.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other than the military, the
police, and small
business, no institution
commands the trust

51:00.791 --> 51:05.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of a majority of us, and even
those are less
trusted than they once were.

51:05.663 --> 51:12.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, the question is, why? One
obvious answer,
there's good reason for this
mistrust. How

51:12.403 --> 51:17.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
confident should we be in banks
after the
financial meltdown, in our
public schools,

51:17.274 --> 51:23.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
given the woeful marks our
students get compared
with other nations, in our
religious leaders,

51:23.247 --> 51:27.918 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
given the criminal sexual
behavior of those
who've spoken in God's name?

51:28.018 --> 51:32.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we're also living in a less
innocent time.
The press was strictly
controlled in World

51:32.890 --> 51:38.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
War II. The failures, strategic
and moral,
in places like Iraq, are on full
display.

51:38.963 --> 51:48.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The private lives of
politicians, once carefully
concealed, are now matters of
public speculation.

51:48.172 --> 51:55.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Movies that celebrated heroes of
the church
or finance now tell very
different stories

51:55.512 --> 52:00.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of greed and sin. And the media
messengers
who show us the feet of clay on
those that

52:00.384 --> 52:05.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stand on the pedestals, well,
they are increasingly
seen as carriers of a partisan
agenda, or

52:06.056 --> 52:07.825 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
guilty of their own failures.

52:07.925 --> 52:13.397 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, deserved or not, the
lengthy disaffection
that so many feel about so many
important

52:13.497 --> 52:18.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
parts of our national life
clearly puts a
heavy burden on anyone asking
for the trust

52:18.969 --> 52:24.675 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of the citizenry. It may,
indeed, reward those
who seek power, not by offering
to ease that

52:24.775 --> 52:26.744 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
disaffection, but to feed it.

52:26.844 --> 52:33.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's worth asking, how does
a nation thrive
when, year after year, our motto
is, in nothing

52:33.350 --> 52:34.952 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we trust?

